"Trenberth K.E.","Attribution of climate variations and trends to human influences and natural variability",2011,"Wiley Interdisciplinary Reviews: Climate Change","2","6",,"925","930",,,10.1002/wcc.142,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80855138230&partnerID=40&md5=87fd0826296d3922dabb53d3b9395d32","National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO, United States","Trenberth, K.E., National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO, United States","Past attribution studies of climate change have assumed a null hypothesis of no role of human activities. The challenge, then, is to prove that there is an anthropogenic component. I argue that because global warming is ""unequivocal"" and 'very likely' caused by human activities, the reverse should now be the case. The task, then, could be to prove there is no anthropogenic component to a particular observed change in climate, although a more useful task is to determine what it is. In Bayesian statistics, this change might be thought of as adding a 'prior'. The benefit of doubt and uncertainties about observations and models are then switched. Moreover, the science community is much too conservative on this issue and too many authors make what are called 'Type II errors' whereby they erroneously accept the null hypothesis. Global warming is contributing to a changing incidence of extreme weather because the environment in which all storms form has changed from human activities. © 2011 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.",,,,,,,,"Stott, P.A., Gillett, N.P., Hegerl, G.C., Karoly, D.J., Stone, D.A., Zhang, X., Zwiers, F., Detection and attribution of climate change: a regional perspective. (2010) WIREs Clim Change, 1, pp. 192-211. , doi:10.1002/wcc.34; Solomon, S., Qin, D., Manning, M., Chen, Z., Marquis, M.C., Qin, D., Manning, M., Mill, H.L., Climate change (2007) The Physical Science Basis, , IPCC (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change). In, eds. Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press; 2007; Schär, C., Vidale, P.L., Lüthi, D., Frei, C., Häberli, C., Liniger, M.A., Appenzeller, C., The role of increasing temperature variability in European summer heat waves. (2004) Nature, 427, pp. 332-336; Allen, M.R., Liability for climate change (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 891-892; Nicholls, N., The insignificance of significance testing. (2001) Bull Am Meteor Soc, 82, pp. 981-986; Schneider, A., Friedl, M.A., Potere, D., A new map of global urban extent from MODIS satellite data. (2009) Environ Res Lett, , 4. doi:10.1088/1748-9326/4/4/044003; Min, S.-K., Zhang, X., Zwiers, F.W., Hegerl, G.C., Human contribution to more intense precipitation extremes. (2011) Nature, 470, pp. 378-381; Pall, P., Aina, T., Stone, D.A., Stott, P.A., Nozawa, T., Hilberts, A.G.J., Lohmann, D., Allen, M.R., Anthropogenic greenhouse gas contribution to flood risk in England and Wales in autumn 2003. (2011) Nature, 470, pp. 382-386; Lin, J.L., Kiladis, G.N., Mapes, B.E., Weickmann, K.M., Sperber, K.R., Lin, W., Wheeler, M.C., Donner, L.J., Tropical intraseasonal variability in 14 IPCC AR4 climate models. Pt I: convective signals. (2006) J Clim, 19, pp. 2665-2690; Scaife, A.A., Woollings, T., Knight, J., Martin, G., Hinton, T., Atmospheric blocking and mean biases in climate models. (2010) J Clim, 23, pp. 6143-6152; Shin, S.-I., Sardeshmukh, P.D., Pegion, K., Realism of local and remote feedbacks on tropical sea surface temperatures in climate models (2010) J Geophys Res, p. 115. , D21110. doi:10.1029/2010JD013927; Deser, C., Phillips, A., Bourdette, V., Teng, H., Uncertainty in climate change projections: the role of internal variability. (2010) Clim Dyn, , doi:10.1007/s00382-010-0977-x; Trenberth, K.E., Fasullo, J., Smith, L., Trends and variability in column-integrated water vapor. (2005) Clim Dyn, 24, pp. 741-758; Santer, B.D., Mears, C., Wentz, F.J., Taylor, K.E., Gleckler, P.J., Wigley, T.M.L., Barnett, T.P., Gillett, N.P., Identification of human-induced changes in atmospheric moisture conten